<LegalLayout
  title="Medicare Billing Help for Seniors"
  description="Understand Medicare allowed amounts, excess charges, and billing basics."
  crumbs={[{ label: 'For Medicare Seniors' }]}
>
  <p>
    Medicare billing has its own vocabulary — <strong>allowed amounts</strong>, participating
    providers, assignment, and supplemental (Medigap) coverage. We help you read statements in plain
    English.
  </p>

  <h2>Medicare allowed amount</h2>
  <p>
    This is what Medicare approves for a service before your Part B coinsurance (usually 20% after the
    deductible). It is the same public data we use in our Fair Price Calculator.
  </p>
  <p>
    <a href="/tools/fair-price/" class="btn btn--primary">Check Medicare benchmark</a>
  </p>

  <h2>Participating vs. non-participating providers</h2>
  <p>
    Most doctors accept Medicare assignment (they agree to Medicare’s allowed amount). Some do not —
    they may charge up to the limiting charge (115% of the allowed amount in many cases). Always ask
    if a provider accepts assignment before non-emergency care.
  </p>

  <h2>Look up procedure codes</h2>
  <p>
    Find CPT codes on your Medicare Summary Notice or provider bill, then read our{' '}
    <a href="/codes/">code guides</a> or use the calculator with your ZIP code for locality-specific
    rates.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a href="/learn/how-to-read-eob/">How to read an EOB →</a> ·
    <a href="/tools/fair-price/?tab=medicare">Medicare Part B estimate →</a>
  </p>
</LegalLayout>
